\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15539679\charrsid15539679 Comments:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid15539679\charrsid15539679 
\par This step is a combination of step 2 of the 8-step algorithm with Thistlethwaite #1.
\par Consider the two UF edges of a solved cube: the UFr edge cannot occupy the place of the UFl edge without being flipped and vice versa. Now consider the places the UFr edge can hit using the following moves: R2, L2, U, D, F, B, r2, l2, u2, d2, f2, b2. It c
a
n hit only one of the two edges pieces at each cube edge. We can thus separate the 24 edges into two sets of 12 edges, and in using these moves in later steps, the two sets of edges will never mingle. I call these "low" and "high" edges - simply because o
ne set is numbered higher than the other. Along each cube edge, there is one low edge and one high edge.
\par Note that by using only half turns of the inner layers, a center piece can be sent only between its current face and the opposite face. In this step a c
enter piece is placed on its correct face or the opposite face and it will not be able to wander off in the later steps.
\par In this step we must take care to match the permutation parities of the low and high edges.\cell }\pard\plain \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\sa200\sl276\slmult1\widctlpar\intbl\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \rtlch\fcs1 
